summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring dynamic class access**\\n\\nI'm considering that while we can't directly access SCL, we might use a natural API to reach it. Could we get SCL from the thread context or during processing? Maybe writing a custom annotation processor loaded with Lombok could work. I realize Javac uses `ProcessorClassLoader` to load processors, but it's not what Lombok uses. Lombok seems to internally create SCL, and I'm trying to figure out if our source can invoke `lombok.Lombok` directly. It seems like that won't be possible.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_29mA61IT2I0nDRJYnkFbgGMp|fc_0cb9747e518cac76016a2396670c64819580e0cad41de4888b", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.38 -type f \\( -name '*.jar' -o -name '*lombok*' \\) | head -50 && find build/tests/org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.38 -maxdepth 5 -type f | head -80"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"find tests/src/org.projectlombok/lombok/1.18.38 -type f \\\\( -name '*.jar' -o -name '*lombok*' \\\\) | head -50 && find build/tests/org.projectlombok:lombok:1.18.38 -maxdepth 5 -type f | head -80\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1519, "output": 1288, "cacheRead": 40448, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 43255, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780717129112, "responseId": "resp_0cb9747e518cac76016a239649c4308195906fffca7f14d1bf"}}
